webpackJsonp([0xe2b0c982398f],{509:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Josh Kuiros",author:"Josh Kuiros"}},markdownRemark:{id:"/Users/kuiros/code/kuiro5.github.io/src/pages/4-underrated-git-commands/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<h3>1. List Branches by Last Modified</h3>\n<p>For the branch hoarders out there, this one is for you.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">git for-each-ref --sort=&#39;-authordate:iso8601&#39; --format=&#39; %(authordate:iso8601)%09%(refname)&#39; refs/head</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3>2. Add Hunks of Patch</h3>\n<p>This is a great alternative to the nuclear git add -A command. It allows you to interactively view each hunk of changes and decide whether or not to stage them.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">git add -p</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3>3. Delete Merged Branches</h3>\n<p>This command checks your local branches (excluding master — more exclusions can be added) and deletes the ones that have been merged.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">git branch --merged | grep -v &quot;\\*|master&quot; | xargs -n 1 git branch -d</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3>4. Log of All Changes</h3>\n<p>This command has saved me many, many times. Reflog tracks all changes in your local repository and gives you a reference point to revert back to. For example, git reset — hard HEAD@{0}.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">git reflog</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p><em>Happy Coding</em> 😊⚡️💻</p>',frontmatter:{title:"4 Underrated Git Commands",date:"October 25, 2017"}}},pathContext:{slug:"/4-underrated-git-commands/",previous:!1,next:{fields:{slug:"/best-way-to-set-up-ctags-with-neovim-and-vim-8/"},frontmatter:{title:"Best Way to Set up Ctags with Neovim and Vim 8"}}}}}});
